\layout Title

On the Stability of a Class of 4-points Exponential-Preserving Subdivision
 Schemes
\layout Author

Daniel Lemire
\layout Address

Acadia University and National Research Council of Canada, lemire@ondelette.com
\layout Abstract

We present a new class of nonlinear 4-point interpolatory subdivision scheme
 preserving functions of the form 
\begin_inset Formula \( ax+b+cz^{x} \)
\end_inset 

.
 We prove the stability (quasi-linearity) and continuity of the schemes.
 Potential applications include processing noisy electromagnetic (EM) decays
 and computer aided geometric design (CAGD).
\layout Section

Introduction
\layout Standard

Soon after Deslauriers and Dubuc first presented their Lagrange interpolation
 scheme, researchers have been building parametric schemes (quote Dyn-levin-greg
ory and Merrien).
 That is, instead of a scheme which only depends on the number of nodes
 or points we consider, we add extra parameters.
 One application of these extra parameters is to taylor the scheme so it
 can have some desired properties.
 For exemple, (quote recent Dyn-Levin article) have shown that given some
 data, they could choose a corresponding parameter 
\begin_inset Formula \( \alpha  \)
\end_inset 

 and build a convexity (convexity/montonoticity???) preserving scheme.
 In general, we would like to taylor the subdivision scheme to a specific
 model.
 There are two possible approach, we can choose an adaptative scheme (quote
 Geof Davis and al.) or we can prefer an adapted scheme (quote Donoho with
 curvelets).
 We follow the second approach and aim to build adapted schemes.
\layout Standard

Motivation: we want to improve the scheme using alternative models for the
 function.
 In particular, we are motivated applications to airborne EM geophysics
 where exponential decays must be processed and studied very carefully.
 Lagrange-type approaches do not exactly reproduce exponentials and while
 they maybe sufficiently accurate for interpolation purposes, they are not
 appropriate in general for analysis purposes through pyramidal or wavelet
 approaches.
