exponential schemes
\layout Standard

We are interesting in measuring how well a given subdivsion scheme can approxima
tion functions.
 One such measure is given by the approximation order of the scheme
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite[definition 2]{KuVD98}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Definition

(Approximation Order) Given a regular sampling 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left\{ f_{i}=f\left( i\Delta x\right) \right\} _{i=0}_{}^{N} \)
\end_inset 

 of a function 
\begin_inset Formula \( f\in C^{p}\left( \left[ 0,1\right] \right)  \)
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula \( N\Delta x=1 \)
\end_inset 

 , we consider 
\begin_inset Formula \( u_{\Delta x} \)
\end_inset 

 the interpolation function generated by a subdivision scheme 
\begin_inset Formula \( S \)
\end_inset 

.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula \( S \)
\end_inset 

 has approximation order 
\begin_inset Formula \( p \)
\end_inset 

 if 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left\Vert u_{\Delta x}-f\right\Vert _{L^{\infty }\left( \left[ 0,1\right] \right) }\leq C\Delta x^{p} \)
\end_inset 

 for a constant 
\begin_inset Formula \( C \)
\end_inset 

 which doesn't depend on 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Delta x \)
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

For a continuous subdivision scheme preserving polynomials of order 
\begin_inset Formula \( p \)
\end_inset 

, it is sufficient for the scheme to converge to a continous function to
 have approximation order 
\begin_inset Formula \( p \)
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{KuVD98}

\end_inset 

.
 Specifically, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula \( 2n- \)
\end_inset 

points Deslauriers-Dubuc scheme has approximation order 
\begin_inset Formula \( 2n \)
\end_inset 

 and thus, as 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Delta x\rightarrow 0 \)
\end_inset 

 so does the approximation error.
 Unfortunately, in practice the data is often available only in a tabular
 format and we can't let 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Delta x\rightarrow 0 \)
\end_inset 

.
 It would seem then that the alternative is to choose 
\begin_inset Formula \( n \)
\end_inset 

 sufficiently large.
 However, it is well-known that 
\layout Proposition

The 
\begin_inset Formula \( 2n- \)
\end_inset 

points Deslauriers-Dubuc scheme makes an error of proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula \( \frac{a^{n}n^{n}}{n!} \)
\end_inset 

 in interpolating an exponential 
\begin_inset Formula \( e^{ax} \)
\end_inset 

 and thus, the error increases when interpolating tabular data.
\layout Proof

Let's consider the tabular data over 
\begin_inset Formula \( x_{k}=\alpha k+\beta  \)
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula \( k=1,...,2n \)
\end_inset 

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula \( e^{ax_{k}} \)
\end_inset 

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula \( p_{n} \)
\end_inset 

 be the unique polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula \( 2n-1 \)
\end_inset 

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula \( p_{n}\left( x_{k}\right) =e^{ax_{k}} \)
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula \( k=1,...,2n \)
\end_inset 

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula \( x\in \left( x_{1},x_{2n}\right)  \)
\end_inset 

 be such that 
\begin_inset Formula \( x\neq x_{k}\, \forall k \)
\end_inset 

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula \( \phi (x)=\left( x-x_{1}\right) ...\left( x-x_{2n}\right)  \)
\end_inset 

 be the unique polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula \( 2n \)
\end_inset 

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula \( \phi \left( x_{k}\right) =x_{k} \)
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula \( k=1,...,2n \)
\end_inset 

, then 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Phi (t)=e^{at}-p_{n}(t)-\frac{\phi (t)}{\phi (x)}\left( e^{ax}-p_{n}(x)\right)  \)
\end_inset 

.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Phi (t)=0 \)
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula \( t=x_{1},...,x_{2n} \)
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( t=x \)
\end_inset 

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Phi (t) \)
\end_inset 

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \( C^{\infty }\left( x_{1},x_{2n}\right)  \)
\end_inset 

, by the Generalized Rolle's theorem, there exist a number 
\begin_inset Formula \( \xi _{n,x}_{}\in \left( x_{1},x_{2n}\right)  \)
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Phi ^{(2n)}(\xi _{n,x})=0 \)
\end_inset 

 and thus using the facts that 
\begin_inset Formula \( \phi ^{(2n)}=(2n)! \)
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( p^{(2n)}_{n}=0 \)
\end_inset 

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula \[
a^{2n}e^{a\xi _{n,x}}-\frac{(2n)!}{\phi (x)}\left( e^{ax}-p_{n}(x)\right) =0\]

\end_inset 

The Deslauriers-Dubuc scheme interpolates the tabular data at 
\begin_inset Formula \( \zeta =\frac{x_{n}+x_{n+1}}{2} \)
\end_inset 

 using 
\begin_inset Formula \( p_{n}(\zeta ) \)
\end_inset 

 and thus makes an error of 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\left| f(\zeta )-p_{n}(\zeta )\right|  & = & \left| \frac{\phi (\zeta )a^{2n}e^{a\xi _{n,x}}}{(2n)!}\right| \\
 & \geq  & \frac{\phi (\zeta )|a|^{2n}e^{-|a|\min \left( x_{1},x_{n}\right) }}{(2n)!}\\
 & = & \frac{|a|^{2n}e^{-|a|\min \left( x_{1},x_{n}\right) }\prod _{k=0}^{n}(k+1/2)^{2}}{(2n)!}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 


