\layout Standard

Is this scheme stable? In order to be usable in practice, a subdivision
 scheme should be stable.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left\Vert f_{k}\right\Vert _{\infty }=\max \left\{ \left| f_{k}\right| |\, k\in Z\right\}  \)
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left\Vert f\right\Vert _{\infty }=\left\Vert f\right\Vert _{L^{\infty }} \)
\end_inset 

 .
\layout Definition

Given two sets of initial data 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{0,k} \)
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( \widetilde{y}_{0,k} \)
\end_inset 

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j,k} \)
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( \widetilde{y}_{j,k} \)
\end_inset 

 be the interpolated data after 
\begin_inset Formula \( j \)
\end_inset 

 iterations, we then call the scheme 
\emph on 
stable
\emph default 
 if 
\begin_inset Formula \( \exists C \)
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left\Vert y_{j,k}-\widetilde{y}_{j,k}\right\Vert _{\infty }\leq C\left\Vert y_{0,k}-\widetilde{y}_{0,k}\right\Vert _{\infty }\]

\end_inset 

where the constant 
\begin_inset Formula \( C \)
\end_inset 

 doesn't depend on 
\begin_inset Formula \( j \)
\end_inset 

.
\layout Definition

Given some data 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j,k} \)
\end_inset 

, we will write 
\begin_inset Formula \( y_{j} \)
\end_inset 

 the unique linear spline interpolating this data.
 It can be verified that 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left\Vert y_{j,k}-\widetilde{y}_{j,k}\right\Vert _{\infty }=\left\Vert y_{j}-\widetilde{y}_{j}\right\Vert _{\infty } \)
\end_inset 

.
 One reason for using linear splines is that fact that the linear component
 in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{4pointexponential}

